Favorite school memory: When Harley dropped me during a three legged race during Homecoming spirit week senior year and my head was bleeding and there were grass stains all over my unicorn suit in front of the whole high school!
Advice to underclassmen: Enjoy the time you have in high school because it will fly by and before you know it your a senior playing your last game and saying goodbye on your last day to the people you grew up with.
Future plans: I will be going to Barton Community College to become a medical assistant.

post_text:
Corona Virus Info & USD #351
This virus is still very new. There is no one in the state of Kansas at this time that is being monitored for this virus. There is no set protocol in place for schools as of yet. Mr. Rinehart and Nurse Becky are in touch with the county health department and State Education officials.
The best line of defense is WASHING HANDS and not putting hands near your face area. The officials also urge people not to panic and spread false rumors amid this outbreak. The state is diligently working on a protocol for schools, but it is ever changing because it is a novel virus with new things learned everyday.
The main concern and focus in the State of Kansas at this time is Influenza. Flu shots are still available. Our school staff is working overtime to assure that our school is sanitized. If your child is sick, please keep them at home.
If you have any questions, please contact the school, your local health department, or your government officials.
Thank you!

post_text:
How Long Does It Take for Shoes to Decompose

Many people do not realize, but a single shoe can have as many as dozens of parts that are sewn, stitched and glued together. Some components of shoes may include rubber parts for the shoe soles. Unfortunately, when shoes end up in landfills, they cause a lot of harm to the environment and the health of people.

The decomposition process for shoes takes many, many years‚Äì‚Äìdecades. As shoes begin to decompose, they begin to release toxins into the air. These toxins are dangerous to human health, which is why people who live close to landfills may have a higher incidence of respiratory illnesses.

The decomposition process is also harmful to the environment because those toxins that go into the air and seep into the soil are poisons that affect our natural environment. What‚Äôs worse is that, depending on the components of any shoe, it can take as many as 80 to 100 years for a shoe to decompose completely. That‚Äôs more years than most human lives on this planet!
